IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: To develop and administer programs to be participated in by low-income residents of Lake, Miner, and such adjunct counties as might wish to participate in order to increase their prospects of breaking out of poverty; to involve said residents, as well as other community groups in the planning and administering of such programs.
IRS990.MissionDescription: InterLakes Community Action Partnership empowers people to live, not just survive.
IRS990.Description: Head Start - The Head Start program provides educational, health, and social services to children from low income families. There are currently 121, 64 & 268 funded children for Early Head Start, Early Head Start Expansion and Head Start, respectively.

Activity2.Description: Weatherization energy assistance is aimed at making housing of low-income persons more energy efficient and less costly for residents. Persons at or below 200% of poverty-level or persons who are eligible for fuel assistance (LIEAP) are eligible for the energy programs. Persons at or below 160% of poverty-level are eligible for furnace repair and replacement programs.

Activity3.Description: Community Services Block Grant - Provides General assistance to all programs offered by Interlakes Community Action Partnership Inc. Programs which identify and eliminate causes of or conditions of poverty.

ActivityOther.Description: Nutrition - Provide free and reduced meals to elderly individuals in both a congregate and home delivered setting. Dining sites are located in 36 communities. 60's plus dining served over 213,628 meals in 2009/2010.Other program services include housing programs, homeless shelter, transportation, emergency services, and other discretionary programs.

Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.Explanation: ICAP has determined there are no amounts to record as assets or liabilities related to uncertain tax positions. Federal returns for the tax years 2007, 2008, and 2009 remain subject to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.

Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Identifier: Procedure for Monitoring Grants in the U.S.:
Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Explanation: Schedule I, Part I, Line 2: Payment is made directly to the vendor on the client's behalf whenever possible. Generally, payments directly to individuals are made as reimbursements. Receipts are required for reimbursement.

Form990ScheduleMPartII.Explanation: Head Start clothing and household items are received as donations but not recorded; these items are considered ineligible contributions. The donor provided fair value of these donations was $27,805 for 2009. The clothing goes directly to program participants.

Received expansion funding in early head start to provide services to 64 children pre-birth to 3.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 1
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The Executive committee can act on behalf of the full board. This committee consists of the Chairman, Vice Chairman, Treasurer, two low income representative board members, and one private sector representative board member.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 2
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: Cheryl Pettys-Howard and Pat Maroney have a business relationship.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 11
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The Executive Director and Finance Director review the 990 in detail. After their review, the 990 is provided to each board member. The Executive Director and/or Finance Director will address any questions or concerns from board members. Whether presented in a board meeting or not, the 990 is not filed until each board member has been given a copy of it and given ample time to review it.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 12c
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: All employees must avoid activities or relationships that conflict with ICAP's interests or adversely affect ICAP's reputation. Employees must disclose actual or potential conflicts to the Executive Director as soon as they become aware of them. Failure to make required disclosures or resolve conflicts of interest satisfactorily can result in discipline up to and including termination of employment. All board members are required to certify by signature that they understand and agree to abide by the Conflict of Interest policy on an annual basis. Any potential conflicts are to be reported to the Secretary. Potential conflicts of interest are reviewed at the Board level. Depending on the nature and severity of the conflict, the Board member will either abstain from voting on the matter-at-hand, or be dismissed from the Board.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 15
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: A wage comparability study was done in May 2009 for all staff. A comparability study is done every three years. All staff members have a performance evaluation annually. Wage scale adjustments are determined for all staff by the full board, based on information provided by the personnel committee.

GeneralExplanation.Explanation: Documents are made available upon request.
